    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Describe the bug\n\nUsing a big hexadecimal number for emplace sometimes gives an unexpected cython compiler type error.\n\n### Code to reproduce the behaviour:\n\n```cython\n# distutils: language=c++\n\nfrom libcpp.vector cimport vector\n\ncdef vector[unsigned int] v\n\nv.emplace_back(0x8000000)  # OK\nv.emplace_back(0x10000000) # OK\nv.emplace_back(0x7fffffff) # OK\nv.emplace_back(0x80000000) # ERROR: Python object cannot be passed as a varargs parameter\nv.emplace_back(<unsigned int>0x80000000) # OK\n```\n\n\n### Expected behaviour\n\nExpected no compile error.\n\n### OS\n\nLinux\n\n### Python version\n\n3.13.3\n\n### Cython version\n\n3.2.4\n\n### Additional context\n\nLooks like Cython will turn a literal bigger than an int32 into an object. But there's a bunch of types that should be tried before defaulting to object. Seems sensible to assume that 0x80000000 is intended to be an unsigned int, and uint64 should probably not become an object on platforms where it is supported?",
